body:
Looks like associated type declaration position in the source code of the trait implementation affects parsing process during compilation.

I tried this code:

``` rust
fn main() {}

trait MyTrait {
    type AssocType;
    fn my_method();
}

struct MyStruct;

impl MyTrait for MyStruct {
    type AssocType = u32;

    #![allow(unused_variables)] // error: an inner attribute is not permitted in this context
    fn my_method() {}
}
```

I expected to see successful compilation.
Instead, this happened:

```
src/main.rs:13:7: 13:8 error: an inner attribute is not permitted in this context
src/main.rs:13     #![allow(unused_variables)]
                     ^
src/main.rs:13:7: 13:8 help: place inner attribute at the top of the module or block
error: aborting due to previous error
```

When I rearrange trait items in the implementation compilation passes successfully.

``` rust
fn main() {}

trait MyTrait {
    type AssocType;
    fn my_method();
}

struct MyStruct;

impl MyTrait for MyStruct {
    #![allow(unused_variables)]
    fn my_method() {}
    type AssocType = u32;
}
```
